INSERT INTO `xz_dialogue` VALUES (1639, 'Here\'s the C++ equivalent of your Python code for finding all valid paths in the modified N-Queens problem, where queens are placed one by one in each row, moving only to the next row when a complete row has been filled:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n\nusing namespace std;\n\nconst int MAXN = 100;\nbool row[MAXN], col[MAXN], p1[MAXN * 2], p2[MAXN * 2];\nvector<vector<pair<int, int>>> ans;\n\nbool check(int i, int j, int n) {\n    return !row[i] && !col[j] && !p1[i + j] && !p2[i - j + n];\n}\n\nvoid dfs(int i, int j, int n, vector<pair<int, int>>& cur) {\n    if (i == n) {\n        if (cur.size() == n) {\n            ans.push_back(cur);\n        }\n        return;\n    }\n\n    if (check(i, j, n)) {\n        cur.push_back(make_pair(i + 1, j + 1));\n        row[i] = col[j] = p1[i + j] = p2[i - j + n] = true;\n        dfs(i + 1, 0, n, cur);\n        row[i] = col[j] = p1[i + j] = p2[i - j + n] = false;\n        cur.pop_back();\n    }\n\n    if (j + 1 < n) {\n        dfs(i, j + 1, n, cur);\n    } else {\n        dfs(i + 1, 0, n, cur);\n    }\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int n;\n    cin >> n;\n    vector<pair<int, int>> cur;\n    dfs(0, 0, n, cur);\n\n    for (int k = 0; k < 3 && k < ans.size(); ++k) {\n        for (auto& p : ans[k]) {\n            cout << p.second << \" \";\n        }\n        cout << endl;\n    }\n    cout << ans.size() << endl;\n\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nThis C++ code maintains the same logic as your Python code. It uses a depth-first search (`dfs`) to recursively explore all possible valid paths. The `check` function verifies if a queen can be placed at a given position by checking the row, column, and both diagonals for conflicts.\n\nNote:\n\n- The `MAXN` constant is set to 100 assuming that the input `n` will not exceed this value. You can adjust it according to your needs.\n- The `ans` vector stores all valid paths found during the search.\n- The `dfs` function takes the current position `(i, j)`, the size `n` of the board, and the current path `cur` as parameters.\n- The `main` function reads the input `n`, initializes an empty path `cur`, and starts the search by calling `dfs`.\n- Finally, it prints the first three paths (if available) and the total number of valid paths found.', 223, 'assistant', '2024-07-02 23:25:27');
