INSERT INTO `xz_dialogue` VALUES (1641, 'Here\'s the C++ version of your Python code, which solves the N-Queens problem with the given constraints:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n\nusing namespace std;\n\nconst int MAXN = 100;\nbool row[MAXN], col[MAXN], p1[MAXN * 2], p2[MAXN * 2];\nvector<pair<int, int>> cur;\nint total = 0;\n\nbool check(int i, int j, int n) {\n    return !row[i] && !col[j] && !p1[i + j] && !p2[i - j + n];\n}\n\nvoid dfs(int i, int j, int n) {\n    if (i == n) {\n        if (cur.size() == n) {\n            total++;\n            if (total <= 3) {\n                for (auto &p : cur) {\n                    cout << p.second << \" \";\n                }\n                cout << endl;\n            }\n        }\n        return;\n    }\n\n    if (check(i, j, n)) {\n        cur.push_back(make_pair(i + 1, j + 1));\n        row[i] = col[j] = p1[i + j] = p2[i - j + n] = true;\n        dfs(i + 1, 0, n);\n        row[i] = col[j] = p1[i + j] = p2[i - j + n] = false;\n        cur.pop_back();\n    }\n\n    if (j + 1 < n) {\n        dfs(i, j + 1, n);\n    } else {\n        dfs(i + 1, 0, n);\n    }\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int n;\n    cin >> n;\n    dfs(0, 0, n);\n    cout << total << endl;\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nIn this C++ code:\n\n- The `MAXN` constant defines the maximum size of the arrays `row`, `col`, `p1`, and `p2`. Adjust it if necessary.\n- The `cur` vector stores the current path (similar to the Python version).\n- The `total` variable keeps track of the total number of valid solutions found.\n- The `check` function verifies if a position `(i, j)` is valid by checking rows, columns, and diagonals.\n- The `dfs` function performs a depth-first search to find all valid solutions.\n- The `main` function reads the input `n`, calls `dfs` to find solutions, and finally prints the total number of solutions found.\n\nCompile and run this C++ code to solve the N-Queens problem as described in your Python code.', 223, 'assistant', '2024-07-02 2